35128593445, "span": {"begin": 975, "end": 980}}, {"id": ["mesh:D007938"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "leukemia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.6526197791099548, "span": {"begin": 991, "end": 999}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:942"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD86", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9934700727462769, "span": {"begin": 1185, "end": 1189}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3383"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD54", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9920881390571594, "span": {"begin": 1194, "end": 1198}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "BALB", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.8873538970947266, "span": {"begin": 1224, "end": 1228}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:10095"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "mice", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9334293007850647, "span": {"begin": 1231, "end": 1235}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:166055"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TMA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9831426739692688, "span": {"begin": 1260, "end": 1263}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9827478528022766, "span": {"begin": 1322, "end": 1326}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-10", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9808166027069092, "span": {"begin": 1331, "end": 1336}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004137"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DNCB", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9958806037902832, "span": {"begin": 1385, "end": 1389}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3565"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-4", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9860073924064636, "span": {"begin": 1401, "end": 1405}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3586"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "IL-10", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9704413414001465, "span": {"begin": 1410, "end": 1415}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:166055"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TMA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9644995927810669, "span": {"begin": 1452, "end": 1455}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DC", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.9156354665756226, "span": {"begin": 1470, "end": 1472}}, {"id": ["mesh:D004137"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "DNCB", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9979943037033081, "span": {"begin": 1533, "end": 1537}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3586"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Anti-IL-10 antibody", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9551745057106018, "span": {"begin": 1556, "end": 1575}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:166055"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "TMA", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.8901675939559937, "span": {"begin": 1605, "end": 1608}}], "text": "There is good agreement between the sequences of biochemical and physiological events leading to skin sensitisation (see [4];[5];[6];[7];[8];[9]).  Using a flow-cytometric assay, the influence of contact sensitisers on endocytic mechanisms in murine Langerhans cells was measured. Epidermal cell suspensions were labelled with a monoclonal antibody directed to MHC class II molecules and pH-sensitive fluorochrome-coupled second step reagents. Study reported that stimulation with well-known sensitising compounds resulted in a partial conservation of the fluorescence intensity due to the internalisation of the labelled complexes into less acidic compartments. For untreated Langerhans cells or in the presence of irritants a significant quenching of fluorescence intensity due to the internalization of the MHC-antibody complexes into acidic compartments was noticed[10]. In the h-CLAT assay measuring the expression of CD86 and CD54 protein markers on the surface of the human monocytic leukemia cell line THP-1, the cell exposure to known non sensitisers does not increase cell biomarker expression. On the contrary, exposure to well-known sensitisers leads to an increase of the CD86 and CD54 expression[11];[12].  In BALB/c mice, topical application of TMA induced rapid cytokine secretion in the skin&mdash;namely IL-4 and IL-10, which was not the case for the skin sensitizer DNCB. Increased IL-4 and IL-10 were also detected in the DLN after TMA exposure, and DC migration to the DLN was confirmed, although delayed behind DNCB-caused migration. Anti-IL-10 antibody ameliorated this response to TMA. (Cumberbatch et al., 2005)", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:37:12 +0000 2026"}